{"id":"2111.15616","submitter":"Herlina Herlina","authors":"Michele Pinelli and Herlina Herlina and Jan G. Wissink and Markus\n  Uhlmann","title":"Direct numerical simulation of turbulent mass transfer at the surface of\n  an open channel flow","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1017/jfm.2021.1080","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We present direct numerical simulation results of turbulent open channel flow\nat bulk Reynolds numbers up to 12000, coupled with (passive) scalar transport\nat Schmidt numbers up to 200. Care is taken to capture the very large scale\nmotions which appear already for relatively modest Reynolds numbers. The\ntransfer velocity at the flat, free surface is found to scale with the Schmidt\nnumber to the power \"-1/2\", in accordance with previous studies and theoretical\npredictions for uncontaminated surfaces. The scaling of the transfer velocity\nwith Reynolds number is found to vary, depending on the Reynolds number\ndefinition used. To compare the present results with those obtained in other\nsystems, we define a turbulent Reynolds number at the edge of the\nsurface-influenced layer. This allows us to probe the two-regime model of\nTheofanous [Turbulent mass transfer at free, gas-liquid interfaces, with\napplications to open-channel, bubble and jet flows. Int. J. Heat Mass Transfer\n19, 613--624, 1976], which is found to correctly predict that small-scale\nvortices significantly affect the mass transfer for turbulent Reynolds numbers\nlarger than 500. It is further established that the root-mean-square of the\nsurface divergence is, on average, proportional to the mean transfer velocity.\nHowever, the spatial correlation between instantaneous surface divergence and\ntransfer velocity tends to decrease with increasing Schmidt number and increase\nwith increasing Reynolds number. The latter is shown to be caused by an\nenhancement of the correlation in high-speed regions, which in turn is linked\nto the spatial distribution of surface-parallel vortices.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 30 Nov 2021 18:12:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-01-19"}
